---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Node Structure">
  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h1 class="section-title">Node Structure</h1>
      <p class="text-muted">Phase 1 Walkthrough - Part 1 of 4</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>The Foundation</h3>
        <p>
          NodeT is the only data structure in the system.
          Everything else are functions on Node. Get this right and everything flows from it.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="diagram">
        <pre class="ascii-art">
// Node struct definition
pub struct NodeT:
    id: usize                    // unique identifier
    tag: String                  // element name (div, p, etc)
    children: ImVector          // persistent vector of Arc-wrapped children
    attrs: ImHashMap             // persistent map of attributes
    content: OptionT             // optional text content

// Concrete DOM node type - Node with String content wrapped in Arc
pub type DomNode = ArcNodeString
        </pre>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Why this design</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>ImVector instead of Vec</strong> - Persistent data structure. When you modify it, the new version shares most internal storage with the old. Essential for structural sharing.</li>
          <li><strong>Arc wrapper</strong> - Atomic reference counting. Multiple owners can share the same Node. Memory freed when last Arc drops.</li>
          <li><strong>Generic T</strong> - Flexibility to store any content type (String, numbers, custom structs).</li>
          <li><strong>ImHashMap</strong> - Persistent map for attributes. Shares structure on modifications.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Node Methods</h2>

      <div class="diagram">
        <pre class="ascii-art">
impl T Clone NodeT:
    pub fn new(id: usize, tag: str) -> Self: ...

    pub fn with_child(mut self, child: ArcNodeT) -> Self: ...
    pub fn with_attr(mut self, k: String, v: String) -> Self: ...
    pub fn with_content(mut self, content: T) -> Self: ...

    pub fn child_count(self) -> usize: ...
    pub fn child(self, idx: usize) -> OptionArcNodeT: ...
        </pre>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Fluent API</h3>
        <p>
          Methods return self for chaining:
        </p>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="ascii-art">
let node = Node.new(1, "div")
    .with_attr("class", "container")
    .with_content("Hello")
          </pre>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div class="container">
      <h2 class="section-title">Key Properties</h2>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Immutability Invariant</h3>
        <p>
          Once a Node is created, it is never mutated in place.
          All mutations create new Node instances. This is why ArcNode
          is automatically thread-safe - immutable data needs no synchronization.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Why Arc</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Rc is single-threaded reference counting</li>
          <li>Arc is atomic - safe across threads (for Phase 2)</li>
          <li>Arc::clone is cheap - just increments reference count</li>
          <li>Arc::ptr_eq checks if two Arcs point to same allocation</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

   <div class="container text-center mb-xl">
     <a href="../tree-builder" class="hero-cta">Next: TreeBuilder</a>
   </div>
</DocsLayout>